<caption id="98C0B4B66A2E557AFF67649C982FF80D" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621333" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6621333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621333/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="285" startId="3.[151,250,1943,1967]" targetBox="[160,1427,455,1916]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="CC00E43E6A2E557AFF67649C982FF80D" blockId="3.[151,1437,1943,2039]" pageId="3" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis id="FECB382C6A2E557AFF67649C9813F855" bold="true" box="[151,274,1943,1967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="285">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="0BBF9FBD6A2E557AFEE764939B15F855" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[279,532,1944,1967]" class="Malacostraca" family="Penaeidae" genus="Rimapenaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="285" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="constrictus">
<emphasis id="FECB382C6A2E557AFEE764939B15F855" box="[279,532,1944,1967]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="285">Rimapenaeus constrictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
—UF 28509, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, female (CL 18.5 mm): A. Cephalothorax, lateral view; B. Thelycum with spermatophore, ventral view. UF 28511, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, male (CL 10.5 mm): C. Petasma, posterior view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="84A5B7B56A29557DFF37639D9C31FDE3" pageId="4" pageNumber="286" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CC00E43E6A29557DFF37639D9C31FDE3" blockId="4.[151,1437,150,933]" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">
<emphasis id="FECB382C6A29557DFF37639D9843FF4A" bold="true" box="[199,322,150,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Rostrum with usually 7 to 9 teeth along entire dorsal margin, without teeth on ventral margin; carapace with two longitudinal sutures; with almost entire dorsal region and anterior part of sides densely setose; branchial region sparsely setose (
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFDFF63D49B75FF03" box="[527,628,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,455,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-157@3.[151,1436,453,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Rimapenaeus constrictus—UF 28509, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, female (CL 18.5 mm):A. Cephalothorax, lateral view; B. Thelycum with spermatophore, ventral view. UF 28511, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, male (CL 10.5 mm): C. Petasma, posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621333/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Figs. 2A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFD7163D49BA6FF03" box="[641,679,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1730,1754]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,188,1700]" captionTargetId="figure-27@5.[151,1436,181,1706]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Rimapenaeus constrictus—MNRJ 30198, Canal Central, Baía de Guanabara, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, female (CL 10.1 mm): A. Cephalothorax, lateral view; B. Thelycum, ventral view. MNRJ 30199, Enseada de Ubatuba, São Paulo, Brazil, male (CL 12.3 mm): C. Petasma, posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621340" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621340/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">4A</figureCitation>
). Abdomen naked except for bands of setae flanking dorsal keel of last 2 or 3 segments. Males with protuberance on sternite 13–14 goblet-shaped, constricted posteriorly. Petasma with inner lamellae soldered together and folded, diverging at the tip, forming two hard, lunate processes with distolateral corners greatly produced as hornlike projections; with two strong hook setae at lamellae divergence point (
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFF6F62649803FE73" box="[159,258,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,455,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-157@3.[151,1436,453,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Rimapenaeus constrictus—UF 28509, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, female (CL 18.5 mm):A. Cephalothorax, lateral view; B. Thelycum with spermatophore, ventral view. UF 28511, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, male (CL 10.5 mm): C. Petasma, posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621333/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Figs. 2C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFEFF62649832FE73" box="[271,307,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1730,1754]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,188,1700]" captionTargetId="figure-27@5.[151,1436,181,1706]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Rimapenaeus constrictus—MNRJ 30198, Canal Central, Baía de Guanabara, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, female (CL 10.1 mm): A. Cephalothorax, lateral view; B. Thelycum, ventral view. MNRJ 30199, Enseada de Ubatuba, São Paulo, Brazil, male (CL 12.3 mm): C. Petasma, posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621340" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621340/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">4C</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="FECB382C6A29557DFEB762649B2DFE73" box="[327,556,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Appendix masculina</emphasis>
(pleopod 2) subquadrate with rows of small stout setae at distal margin (
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFA94626499BBFE57" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1933,1957]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,960,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-397@4.[151,1437,957,1910]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Rimapenaeus constrictus—UF 28511, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, male (CL 10.5 mm): A. Thoracic sternites 13–14; B. Appendix masculina (pleopod 2). UF 28509, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, female (CL 18.5 mm): C. Exopod of fifth pereopod (right); D. Telson, dorsal view, terminal spine lost." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621338" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621338/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Figs. 3B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFF38629999EDFE57" box="[200,236,402,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1775,1799]" captionTargetBox="[166,1427,188,1742]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[151,1436,181,1751]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Rimapenaeus constrictus—MNRJ 30199, Enseada de Ubatuba, São Paulo, Brazil, male (CL 12.3 mm):A. Thoracic sternites 13–14. Male (CL 14.4 mm): B. Thoracic sternites 13–14; C. Appendix masculina (pleopod 2). Female (CL 17.7 mm): D. Thelycum with spermatophore, ventral view. Female (CL 20 mm): E. Exopod of fifth pereopod (right and left); F. Thelycum, ventral view. MNRJ 30198, Canal Central, Baía de Guanabara, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, female (CL 10.1 mm): G. Telson, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621344/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">5C</figureCitation>
). Thelycum anterior margin of plates of sternite 14 strongly convex, evenly rounded, notched in middle; anterior margin of median protuberance on sternite 13 convex or subangulate (
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFBFC62BC9D6EFE2B" box="[1036,1135,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1730,1754]" captionTargetBox="[161,1428,188,1700]" captionTargetId="figure-27@5.[151,1436,181,1706]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Rimapenaeus constrictus—MNRJ 30198, Canal Central, Baía de Guanabara, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, female (CL 10.1 mm): A. Cephalothorax, lateral view; B. Thelycum, ventral view. MNRJ 30199, Enseada de Ubatuba, São Paulo, Brazil, male (CL 12.3 mm): C. Petasma, posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621340" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621340/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Figs. 4B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFB8B62BD9D98FE2B" box="[1147,1177,438,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1775,1799]" captionTargetBox="[166,1427,188,1742]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[151,1436,181,1751]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Rimapenaeus constrictus—MNRJ 30199, Enseada de Ubatuba, São Paulo, Brazil, male (CL 12.3 mm):A. Thoracic sternites 13–14. Male (CL 14.4 mm): B. Thoracic sternites 13–14; C. Appendix masculina (pleopod 2). Female (CL 17.7 mm): D. Thelycum with spermatophore, ventral view. Female (CL 20 mm): E. Exopod of fifth pereopod (right and left); F. Thelycum, ventral view. MNRJ 30198, Canal Central, Baía de Guanabara, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, female (CL 10.1 mm): G. Telson, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621344/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">5F</figureCitation>
). Exopods of fifth pair of pereopods long, reaching, or almost reaching level of distomesial extremity of basis and telson with 2 rounded carinae, tapering to short acuminate tip, armed on either side with one stout seta (
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFBD662F49DA9FDE3" box="[1062,1192,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1933,1957]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,960,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-397@4.[151,1437,957,1910]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Rimapenaeus constrictus—UF 28511, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, male (CL 10.5 mm): A. Thoracic sternites 13–14; B. Appendix masculina (pleopod 2). UF 28509, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, female (CL 18.5 mm): C. Exopod of fifth pereopod (right); D. Telson, dorsal view, terminal spine lost." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621338" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621338/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Figs. 3C, D</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFB2E62F59C22FDE3" box="[1246,1315,510,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1775,1799]" captionTargetBox="[166,1427,188,1742]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[151,1436,181,1751]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Rimapenaeus constrictus—MNRJ 30199, Enseada de Ubatuba, São Paulo, Brazil, male (CL 12.3 mm):A. Thoracic sternites 13–14. Male (CL 14.4 mm): B. Thoracic sternites 13–14; C. Appendix masculina (pleopod 2). Female (CL 17.7 mm): D. Thelycum with spermatophore, ventral view. Female (CL 20 mm): E. Exopod of fifth pereopod (right and left); F. Thelycum, ventral view. MNRJ 30198, Canal Central, Baía de Guanabara, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, female (CL 10.1 mm): G. Telson, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621344/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">5E, G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="84A5B7B56A29557DFF3761289DC5FC5F" pageId="4" pageNumber="286" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="CC00E43E6A29557DFF3761289DC5FC5F" blockId="4.[151,1437,150,933]" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">
<emphasis id="FECB382C6A29557DFF376128983AFDC7" bold="true" box="[199,315,547,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Remarks.</emphasis>
All diagnostic features of 
<taxonomicName id="0BBF9FBD6A29557DFD8461289A10FDC6" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[628,785,547,572]" class="Malacostraca" family="Penaeidae" genus="Rimapenaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="286" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="constrictus">
<emphasis id="FECB382C6A29557DFD8461289A10FDC6" box="[628,785,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">R. constrictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including that mentioned in 
<bibRefCitation id="A82E99CF6A29557DFB9A61289C65FDC7" author="Perez Farfante, I." box="[1130,1380,547,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="286" pagination="1 - 32" refId="ref7535" refString="Perez Farfante, I. (1988) Illustrated Key to Penaeoid Shrimps of Commerce in the Americas. NOAA Technical Report, NMFS, 64, 1 - 32." type="journal article" year="1988">Pérez Farfante (1988)</bibRefCitation>
key, were analyzed in all examined specimens from both lineages. Small distinctions were observed in some specimens, but none clear pattern that allows the morphological separation of the two lineages found in molecular data was observed. At the present level of morphological observation, these distinctions from specific diagnosis were considered intraspecific variations once that they were observed also between specimens from the same locality. The main intraspecific variation observed was in protuberance on sternite 13–14 of males that according to 
<bibRefCitation id="A82E99CF6A29557DFB0861DC99E3FCEF" author="Perez Farfante, I." pageId="4" pageNumber="286" pagination="1 - 32" refId="ref7535" refString="Perez Farfante, I. (1988) Illustrated Key to Penaeoid Shrimps of Commerce in the Americas. NOAA Technical Report, NMFS, 64, 1 - 32." type="journal article" year="1988">Perez Farfante (1988)</bibRefCitation>
is goblet-shaped, constricted posteriorly. The same was observed herein in some Ubatuba (
<collectingRegion id="0E7B2ADC6A29557DFB2861F09C4DFCEC" box="[1240,1356,763,790]" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">São Paulo</collectingRegion>
) specimens (
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFF136014983AFCC3" box="[227,315,798,825]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1775,1799]" captionTargetBox="[166,1427,188,1742]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[151,1436,181,1751]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Rimapenaeus constrictus—MNRJ 30199, Enseada de Ubatuba, São Paulo, Brazil, male (CL 12.3 mm):A. Thoracic sternites 13–14. Male (CL 14.4 mm): B. Thoracic sternites 13–14; C. Appendix masculina (pleopod 2). Female (CL 17.7 mm): D. Thelycum with spermatophore, ventral view. Female (CL 20 mm): E. Exopod of fifth pereopod (right and left); F. Thelycum, ventral view. MNRJ 30198, Canal Central, Baía de Guanabara, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, female (CL 10.1 mm): G. Telson, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621344/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
) but in 
<collectingRegion id="0E7B2ADC6A29557DFE65601498E7FCC3" box="[405,486,799,825]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Florida</collectingRegion>
and other Ubatuba (
<collectingRegion id="0E7B2ADC6A29557DFD3F60149A44FCC0" box="[719,837,799,826]" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">São Paulo</collectingRegion>
) specimens it is almost rounded, not acute anteriorly and not constricted posteriorly (
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFE0960489B5AFCA7" box="[505,603,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1933,1957]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,960,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-397@4.[151,1437,957,1910]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Rimapenaeus constrictus—UF 28511, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, male (CL 10.5 mm): A. Thoracic sternites 13–14; B. Appendix masculina (pleopod 2). UF 28509, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, female (CL 18.5 mm): C. Exopod of fifth pereopod (right); D. Telson, dorsal view, terminal spine lost." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621338" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621338/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Figs. 3A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFD9760499B8BFCA7" box="[615,650,834,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1775,1799]" captionTargetBox="[166,1427,188,1742]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[151,1436,181,1751]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Rimapenaeus constrictus—MNRJ 30199, Enseada de Ubatuba, São Paulo, Brazil, male (CL 12.3 mm):A. Thoracic sternites 13–14. Male (CL 14.4 mm): B. Thoracic sternites 13–14; C. Appendix masculina (pleopod 2). Female (CL 17.7 mm): D. Thelycum with spermatophore, ventral view. Female (CL 20 mm): E. Exopod of fifth pereopod (right and left); F. Thelycum, ventral view. MNRJ 30198, Canal Central, Baía de Guanabara, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, female (CL 10.1 mm): G. Telson, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621344/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">5B</figureCitation>
). The 
<emphasis id="FECB382C6A29557DFD3F60489AAEFCA7" box="[719,943,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">appendix masculina</emphasis>
(pleopod 2) was not described previously to this species, but none variation was observed between the examined material. At the thelycum, the middle notch on plates of sternite 14 is wider in specimens with the spermatophore plug inserted (
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFBD360809D87FC5F" box="[1059,1158,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,455,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-157@3.[151,1436,453,1920]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Rimapenaeus constrictus—UF 28509, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, female (CL 18.5 mm):A. Cephalothorax, lateral view; B. Thelycum with spermatophore, ventral view. UF 28511, Jacksonville, Florida, USA, male (CL 10.5 mm): C. Petasma, posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621333/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">Figs. 2B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="5484F8BB6A29557DFB6160819DB7FC5F" box="[1169,1206,906,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1775,1799]" captionTargetBox="[166,1427,188,1742]" captionTargetId="figure-17@6.[151,1436,181,1751]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Rimapenaeus constrictus—MNRJ 30199, Enseada de Ubatuba, São Paulo, Brazil, male (CL 12.3 mm):A. Thoracic sternites 13–14. Male (CL 14.4 mm): B. Thoracic sternites 13–14; C. Appendix masculina (pleopod 2). Female (CL 17.7 mm): D. Thelycum with spermatophore, ventral view. Female (CL 20 mm): E. Exopod of fifth pereopod (right and left); F. Thelycum, ventral view. MNRJ 30198, Canal Central, Baía de Guanabara, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, female (CL 10.1 mm): G. Telson, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6621344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6621344/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="286">5D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
